[1
Date: Sat, 30 May 1998 12:29:22 -0500
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj2020@vt8200.vetmed.lsu.edu>
Source: News media

SALT LAKE CITY -- Five more wild horses have tested positive for a deadly
virus and land managers are resigned to the likelihood they may end up
killing as many as half of the animals in one large herd to stop the virus
from spreading. The rate of infection for animals with Equine Infectious
Anemia in a herd of more than 150 horses continues at nearly 50 percent and
officials no longer expect it to get much better. The normal rate of
infection is well below 1 percent.
The Bureau of Land Management (BLM) and the Humane Society of America are
negotiating to try to spare a number of foals that tested positive but
might not really be sick. So far, eight young horses are scheduled to be
euthanized.
Tests on nine horses gathered Tuesday showed five were infected, including
one foal. That's in keeping with the rate of infection found in 53 horses
from the same herd gathered earlier. Of those, 27 -- including seven foals
-- tested positive.
State veterinarian Mike Marshall has ordered the BLM to destroy all
infected animals by Monday at 5 p.m. That order has sparked outrage from
the Humane Society of America, which is concerned that some of the foals
may be carrying [maternal antibodies passed on by their mothers [to the
foals in the maternal colostrum ... MHJ and might not actually be sick.
Marshall acknowledged that a few of the foals may have "passive antibodies"
to the disease. "My job is to prevent disease in healthy horses," said
Marshall. "I have to ask if those one or two foals is worth the risk to all
of the healthy population."
It is expected that the roundup in the 142,000-acre Bonanza herd management
area -- where all of the sick animals have been found -- should be
completed by [next Tuesday. The area is about 140 miles southeast of Salt
Lake.
