[2
Date: Fri, 29 May 1998 22:20:07 -0600
From: hnash@wyoming.com (Hal Nash)

Is there any support for NOT euthanizing the infected horses and letting
natural selection build up a population of naturally immune (or at least
surviving) individuals? If the population of horses was allowed to live
and die, then would not a genetically "strong" herd be developed? In the
long run, this would take care of the problem of transmission to domestic
horses because the disease would either be absent or present at only a low
level in the wild horse population.
Isn't human intervention here circumventing the process of natural selection?
--
Hal B. Nash
Asst. Professor of Biology
Western Wyoming College
Rock Springs WY 82901
[The problem with EIA is that infected animals have a chronic viraemia and
the virus demonstrates an active mutability. My colleague Chuck Issel was
well funded because EIV was once considered an animal virus model for HIV.
The horse industry in this country is too valuable to put it at risk from
EIA. - Mod.MHJ
